2ae5d600-1334-459e-885c-a04f87b71c34.0e29c706-4d3c-47c4-8e58-a99307d47bc8.description=
 
This operation reads the content of a file. The operation can be used to read the entire file content in one step or to iterate the file line by line.

Inputs\:
    source - The full path and filename of the file to be read. A UNC path can be supported as the source file path.
    filter -  Regular expression filter to be applied to each line (leave blank for no filter). If this filter is not blank, all rows that contain the filter string will be returned. If no match is found, no lines will be returned.
    store - Whether to store results in the session for retrieval. If "store" is set to true, then all matching lines are pushed into the Session and then subsequent calls to the operation results in the next line being returned.  If set to "false", the file will be iterated and in any iteration the number of remaining lines that matched the "filter" will be returned.
Valid values \: true, false
    delimiter - If specified, the entire content of the file  will be read, the specified value will be used as a delimiter between the rows and  the resulting content will be returned. If left blank, the next row will be returned for each subsequent call. 
    user - Username to use for thread impersonation on the RAS host when reading.
    password - Password for the user.
    eofReset -  If set to true, after the No More response has been returned once, the operation will restart reading the file from the beginning on the next call.
Valid values\: true, false
    characterSet - The character set of the file to read from. For invalid or empty input value the default encoding will be used. 
Valid values\: UTF-8, UTF-16 and UTF-32 
Default value\: UTF-8

Responses\:
    more lines - More lines are available to be read in the session.
    no more lines - No lines are available for reading in the session.
    failure - If something went wrong. 

Results\:
    returnCode - This is the primary output. It is 0 if the operation completed successfully  (or if more rows are available when iterate is set to true), 1 if no more items (if iterate is set to true) and -1 in case of failure. 
    COUNT- The number of lines that matched the filter, or if no filter specified, the total lines read (if iterate is false, or delimiter is not null). Otherwise, it returns the number of lines remaining in the session. This result is only returned in line-by-line mode.
    returnResult - Each row by turn (if iterate is true and delimiter is blank) or all rows separated by the delimiter (if iterate is true and delimiter is not blank).
    exception - An exception message if the operation fails.

Note\:
1. If you are using UTF-8 special characters(for example japanese characters), please ensure that your file is encoded in UTF-8 and not in ANSI wich is the default file encoding in windows when you are creating a new file.
2. The "filter" and "eofReset" fields are taken into consideration only if iterate is set to true. Otherwise, they have no impact on the result.
3. If i"store" is set to "true" and "delimiter" is not null, the entire file may or may not still be fully read at once, depending on size. 
4. If "store" is set to "true", then all matching lines are pushed into the Session and then, subsequent calls to the operation, result in the next line being returned.

Examples\:
    The following examples are used to illustrate the behavior of the operation for three specific use cases. For these examples, the operation will use as the input source a file called "example.txt", with the absolute path "C\:\Program Files\example.txt" and the following content\:
        "line1
         line2
         line3
         line4"
1. This is a valid inputs example for reading the content of a file, when the "store" input field is set to "true" and the "delimiter" input field is not left blank\:
        source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        filter\:
        store\: true
        delimiter\: ,
        eofReset\: false
        characterSet\: UTF-8
    In this case, the "returnResult" output field of the operation will have the following value\: line1,line2,line3,line4
2. This is a valid inputs example for reading the content of a file, when the "store" input field is set to "true" and the "delimiter" input field is left blank\:
        source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        filter\:
        store\: true
        delimiter\:
        eofReset\: false
        characterSet\: UTF-8
    In this case, the file will be iterated row by row in four subsequent calls. At each call, the "returnResult" output field of the operation will contain the value of one line from the file, in the same order as they are found in the source file (i.e. line1, line2, lin3, line4). 
3. This is a valid inputs example for reading the content of a file, when the "store" input field is set to "false" and the "delimiter" input field is left blank\:       
        source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        filter\:
        iterate\: false
        delimiter\:
        eofReset\: false
        characterSet\: UTF-8
    In this case, all matching lines will be iterated and the "returnResult" field will contain, at each iteration, the number of lines remaining to be iterated (i.e\: 4, 3, 2, 1).
2ae5d600-1334-459e-885c-a04f87b71c34.2e650255-4d08-494a-8329-919eb70ee6ca.description=
Deletes the file or directory specified.

Input Parameters\:
source - full path to file/directory to be removed (can be a UNC path)
user - Username to use for thread impersonation on the RAS host while deleting.
password - Password for the user.

Responses\:
success - The specified path was successfuly removed.
failure - Unable to remove file/directory.
2ae5d600-1334-459e-885c-a04f87b71c34.40046ede-9990-4215-b4a2-5f3b35575436.callout=Description \: Ce flow permet d'appeler le script Python de formattage du rapport. Il récupére le contenu de la variable globale "VF.reportInfos" (rapport brut) et apppelle le script de formattage. 2ae5d600-1334-459e-885c-a04f87b71c34.556eac9b-3608-44d3-8406-b1c3398f3859.description=Description\: ------------- Permet de sélectionner un Worker Group au hasard. Le flow récupère en dynamique la liste des Worker Group puis il en prend un au hasard. Il créé les variables GLOBALES "overrideJRAS" et "overrideNRAS" en leur affectant le nom du Worker Group déterminé. Inputs\: -------- N/A Inputs Examples\: -------------------- N/A Outputs\: ---------- ou.errorMsg \: Message d'erreur en cas de dysfonctionnement Revision\: ---------- 18-10-2017 \: Capgemini - FBI version initiale Configuration\: ---------------- N/A 2ae5d600-1334-459e-885c-a04f87b71c34.5d5848ea-56a4-4865-8276-6ce3561ebe95.description=
 
Check to see if the value stored in a specified flow variable, denoted by key, is null.

Inputs\:
    keyName - The key to check, i.e. the name of the flow variable. 
    trimSpaces - If set on "true" then all the whitespaces will be removed from the value stored. 
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false

Returns\: 
    The value in the specified key, i.e. flow variable with all whitespaces removed.

Responses\:
    isNull - If the key is a null pointer, i.e. the flow variable doesn't have an assigned value.
    notNull - If some value is stored in the key, i.e the flow variable has a value assigned. 

Notes\: 
    1. If the "trimSpaces" input is set on "true" and the value from "keyName" contains only whitespaces then the response will be "isNull". 
    2. If the "trimSpaces" input is set on "false" and the value from "keyName" contains only whitespaces then the response will be "notNull". 
    3. If any other value than "true" or "false" is passed on "trimSpaces" input then the default value (false) will be used.
2ae5d600-1334-459e-885c-a04f87b71c34.75d4ccf4-1b60-41f9-9421-61f33a99f1e6.description=Ce sous-flow permet de lancer un script Python sur un des RAS. Le script Python doit répondre à une norme de localisation et de nommage \: - le script doit être nommé _.pyc (seul le script compilé doit être présent sur le RAS) - le script doit présent dans la répertoire D\:/adm_cst/usrlib/pylibs/CASUS/ Le script est exécuté avec l'interpréteur Python 2.7.3 (géré par l'équipe) ou avec l'interpréteur Python Opsware (fourni par HP). Ce dernier est nécessaire pour tout script devant accéder à l'API SA. Inputs \: I_scriptCasus Nom du script Python a exécuter, sans l'extension (par exemple, pour l'entrée valant USD_ConnectivityCheck doit correspondre le script compilé D\:/adm_cst/usrlib/pylibs/CASUS/USD/USD_ConnectivityCheck.pyc) I_varsThatMustNotBeNull Constructeur des arguments passés au script. Liste des options obligatoires. I_vars2optionsWithArgs Constructeur des arguments passés au script. Liste des options avec argument. I_vars2optionsWithoutArgs Constructeur des arguments passés au script. Liste des options sans argument I_pythonSA Indique si l'interpréteur Python Opsware doit être utilisé (si __UNDEFINED__ ou non renseigné, c'est l'interpréteur Python 2.7.3 qui sera utilisé) I_scriptTimeout Durée de vie du script vis à vis de HPOO ATTENTION, toutes les inputs utilisées pour contrôler et construire la ligne d'arguments du script doivent respecter les constraintes suivantes \: - nom de l'input en adéquation avec l'option du script (Ie. si par exemple le script utilise l'option --toto, il faut que l'input associée soit nommée I_toto) - l'input doit être déclarée comme entrée de ce sous-flow. C'est obligatoire pour que le sous-flow ait la variable en visibilité. Ouputs \: Cf. l'onglet Outputs. Pour parser un élément de l'Ouput _DATAS, utiliser un filtre XpathQuery, par exemple \: /DATAS/DATA(NAME\='opStatus')/VALUE/text() /DATAS/DATA(NAME\='systemVersion')/VALUE/text() 2ae5d600-1334-459e-885c-a04f87b71c34.8bd0cd82-bddb-4398-97e7-25d708002130.callout=Codification \: in.xxxxx \: paramètre d'entrée (modifiable) vf.xxxxx \: variable de flow (modifiable) cf.xxxxx \: variable issue de la configuration du flow (modifiable) .xxxxx \: variable liée au template (non modifiable) YY \= IN, VF, CF 2ae5d600-1334-459e-885c-a04f87b71c34.90699cd6-42be-40ce-97c3-b1facaa6851b.description=
Creates a directory

Inputs\:
path - The path of the directory to create.
user - The username to use for thread impersonation on the RAS host when creating directory.
password - The password for user.

Responses\:
success - The directory created was successfully created.
failure - Failed to create directory.

2ae5d600-1334-459e-885c-a04f87b71c34.c0b90a1b-bcfa-4447-ab3d-cd3348343884.description=
Checks to see if a path is an existing file or folder.

Inputs\:
source - The full path path to check. This can be either a local path such as c\:\test.txt, or a unc path such as \\testhost\test.txt. This path is relative to the Windows RAS host that the operation is running on.
user - Username to use for thread impersonation on the RAS host when reading.
password - Password for username.

Responses\:
failure - The operation failed. The path does not exist.
success - The operation succeeded.
2ae5d600-1334-459e-885c-a04f87b71c34.cbd54ebc-764d-49e5-b4da-33e76bf322fd.description=
This operation does not do anything. It can be used to filter flow variables by defining them as inputs and filtering them in the Results tab.

Inputs\:
    field1 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field2 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field3 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field4 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the value of  "field1" as it was specified at input or when filtered. 

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
2ae5d600-1334-459e-885c-a04f87b71c34.cf6927c6-3df1-40b8-9b73-1c109588deb9.description=
Writes the data from "contents" input to the requested file. The operation can be used to overwrite existing content of the file,  append extra lines to it or even create a new file.

Input Parameters\:
file                - Full path to file (can be a UNC path, will attempt to create directory structure). If the file does not exist it is created first.
contents        - The contents to write to the file. Contents can have a new line delimiter which is also given as input to the operation, but it is optional. Example\: "This is line no. 01\nThis is line no. 2\n" where \n is the delimiter.
user              - Username to use for thread impersonation on the RAS host for this operation.
password      - Password for the user.
delimiter       - Specifies the newline delimiter (\n, \r\n, etc) that is used for the "contents" input.
overwrite      - Specifies whether to overwrite the file or append to it. By default, the used value is true. Accepted values\: true, false or the empty string. If this is left empty, the file will be overwritten.
characterSet - The character encoding used to write to the file. The default is UTF-8. Example values\: windows-1252, UTF-16, UTF-16BE,  ISO-8859-1, US-ASCII, Shift_JIS etc.

Responses\:
success - The contents were written to the file.
failure - The operation did not succeed in writing the contents to file.
